  "text": "When opiate agonists or antagonists were superfused on the longitudinal or circular muscle strips from human sigmoid colon, neither dynorphin( 1-13) nor U50,488 altered spontaneous contractions, but both dramatically reduced the amplitude of contractions elicited by electrical stimulation. The effects of both K ligands were blocked by the K antagonist nor-binaltorphimine but not by the 6 antagonist ICI 174,864, indicating involvement of the K receptors in this action [CITATION_1] . In the conscious rat, the enkephalinase inhibitor acetorphan increased the percentage of long spike bursts going to the distal colon, as occurs typically after feeding, and it reinforced the increase induced by feeding. This indicated a role for the opiate system in electromyographic activity of the colon, and this idea was supported by the naloxone reversibility of the action [CITATION_2] .",
